  "community_article": "A local community can protect its forest and still use wood carefully. The model counts carbon in standing trees, soil, and long-lived products, then compares those benefits with habitat, recreation, cultural use, and local product needs. For the managed pine production forest, a longer harvest interval with more wood going into durable products stores substantial carbon over 100 years while keeping jobs and stewardship revenue. The recommendation is not to cut every forest: the old-growth reserve remains best left uncut. The point is to match the plan to the forest, monitor the carbon account, and move gradually so residents, workers, and forest users can see the tradeoffs.",
